<P>
WORLD IN BRIEF; RWANDA; 150 SOLDIERS ARRIVE IN 'SAFE ZONE' 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Times Staff and Wire Services 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 The Tutsi-led government sent about 150 soldiers to begin taking control of 
southwestern Rwanda, where half a million Hutus have sought U.N. protection 
against feared reprisals for massacres during the country's devastating civil 
war. The new government, trying to consolidate its July victory, has promised 
it will not tolerate reprisals against Hutus for the slaughter of at least 
500,000 people, mostly civilians from Rwanda's Tutsi minority. Shaharyar Khan, 
the U.N. special representative for Rwanda, said the transition from U.N. to 
government control will take two to four weeks. 
</P>
