<HEADLINE>
<P>
PRO FOOTBALL / DAILY REPORT; RAMS; HENLEY CONTRACT NOT QUITE DONE 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By T.J. SIMERS 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Cornerback Darryl Henley reported to Rams Park on Tuesday, met with Coach 
Chuck Knox, but left without signing a contract. 
</P>
<P>
 "I expect it to be done," said John Shaw, Ram president."We're just waiting 
for some documents detailing the financial terms (of Henley's $2 million 
bail)." 
</P>
<P>
 The Rams were told they would have those documents at noon Tuesday, but 
Henley's agent, Marvin Demoff, had not delivered the completed paperwork by the 
end of the business day. 
</P>
<P>
 The team would like to have Henley signed today so he can practice in 
preparation for Sunday's game in Atlanta. 
</P>
<P>
 Henley has been indicted for cocaine possession and distribution and awaits a 
January trial. However, he has received permission from the NFL to play, and a 
federal judge ruled he may travel with the team if he, or a responsible third 
party, secures a $2 million bond. 
</P>
<P>
 Ram officials expressed no alarm at Tuesday's delay in getting Henley's 
signature on a contract. They said they were only being cautious in awaiting 
the arrival of pertinent documents that will allow him to travel. 
</P>
<P>
 * 
</P>
<P>
 Knox, who has had a history of quietly helping various charitable efforts, has 
told team officials to take $2,000 raised in fines from players weighing in 
overweight, and direct it toward the feeding of the hungry in Rwanda. T.J. 
SIMERS 
</P>
