<HEADLINE>
<P>
ORANGE COUNTY FOCUS: COSTA MESA; ADULT HEALTH CARE CENTER TO OPEN 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By TOM RAGAN 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 An adult health care center will open Thursday to provide health, therapeutic 
and social services to frail, elderly, physically or mentally impaired adults. 
</P>
<P>
 The Harbor Adult Health Care will be open from 9 a.m. to 3 p.m. Monday through 
Friday inside the Rea Community Center, 661 W. Hamilton St. 
</P>
<P>
 Huntington Beach and Fountain Valley residents are also welcome to the health 
services, said Beverly Daniels, the program director of the nonprofit 
organization, which is certified by the Medi-Cal program. 
</P>
<P>
 "There is a real need in the community for a health care center like this 
one," Daniels said. "This is specifically geared for a special population that 
is having medical problems. An average healthy senior citizen would not come to 
something like this." 
</P>
<P>
 A registered nurse, a certified social worker, a psychologist, an activity 
coordinator and a consulting doctor will assess the individual's health needs 
at the center, then offer a variety of services, including nutritional and 
psychological counseling, physical therapy, blood pressure readings and insulin 
injections. 
</P>
<P>
 Information on diseases such as Parkinson's and Alzheimer's will be available, 
along with a list of the symptoms. The registered nurse will be able to 
administer medication. 
</P>
<P>
 Patients rebounding from strokes can also receive help at the center, whether 
it is learning how to walk or talk or use their limbs. 
</P>
<P>
 Part of the goal of the center, Daniels said, is to prevent placing the 
elderly in convalescent homes by dealing with their health problems in advance. 
</P>
<P>
 Dances and sing-alongs are a few activities that will take place at the center 
for those who are able. Exercise classes will be held, and current events will 
be talked about. 
</P>
<P>
 Fees may be covered through health insurance, managed care programs, medical 
benefits or private pay. Programs are available for those who cannot afford the 
services. 
</P>
<P>
 For more information, call (714) 548-9331.TOM RAGAN 
</P>
</TEXT>
